As with our other machine learning architectures, spancat is flexible and customizable.

For example, you can swap out the MaxOutWindowEncoder into a MishWindowEncoder by simply updating the config file!

https://t.co/EB7AAAbuPa
Scoring: we perform multilabel classification on these pooled spans, thereby returning model predictions and label probabilities

Embedding: we obtain the tok2vec representation of the candidate spans so we can work on them numerically.

Pooling: we reduce the sequences to make the model more robust, then encode the context using a window encoder https://t.co/8US3i2SYOh

The suggested spans go into the classifier, which then predicts the correct label for every span. 

By including the context of the whole span, the classifier can catch informative words deep within it.

We can divide the classifier into three steps: Embedding, Pooling & Scoring

These suggester functions can be completely rule-based, depend on annotations from other components, or use machine learning approaches.

Read how this works here: https://t.co/YlKaacIv2V

Our typical workflow today
  
Azure DevOps ex TFS does the versioning for us, no more manual doing necessary.
  
Currently we work with a hybrid solution having a file share and an Azure DevOps pipeline.

For the future we plan with a solution that fully relies on Azure DevOps. https://t.co/ukzSUyj6ln

Our typical workflow in the past

A file is to be edited for this we copy it and work in the copy and add the source with a version number to _ARCHIVE

But this step is very repetitive and luckily no longer needed! 

Today we only use this procedure in special cases.

The project directory 

If something in between is needed it can simply be added e.g. 011 or 016 or 999

It is more a guideline it does not have to run like this it should just reflect the processing flow

Nothing is fixed and may always be decided differently.

The project directory
  
010 Everything that is read in as data or API requests
015 The actual processing or modulation the real magic happens here
020 What generates an output
030 Outputs as DB-File or data file

Any of these rules can be broken for the sake of usability! https://t.co/4KClk32gBJ

The overview of the projects

This should be followed by a project name that is as self-explanatory as possible. 

If the project has a client reference, we usually add this to the name.
  
You memorize brands very well and this helps in remembering the project and what it does. https://t.co/GSW5S9bkI4

The overview of the projects
  
Followed by the year comes the abbreviation of the project-owner or the one who created the project.  
  
So there can be forks of the same project by team members sometimes this is very handy

The overview of the projects

For folders start with the year followed by the month.
  
It makes more sense to sort projects by time than by first letter. 

The probability that you work in a new project is the highest.

This saves thousands of clicks over the year. https://t.co/x2EZtjdXmf

The Five Dysfunctions of a Team: A Leadership Fable

The book reveals the five dysfunctions of why teams even the best ones-often struggle.

It outlines a powerful model and actionable steps that can be used to overcome these common hurdles and build a cohesive, effective team. https://t.co/jpmStDL05M

Inattention to Results

If the team members don‚Äôt feel accountable, they put their own needs [ego, recognition, career development etc.] ahead of the team goals. 

The result is that the team loses.

Avoidance of Accountability

Lack of commitment results in team members not making each other accountable. If one has not bought into the decision, they won‚Äôt make their peers too accountable.

Lack of Commitment

Fear of conflict results in lack of commitment. 

As team members have not bought into the decisions, they don‚Äôt feel committed to the same which resulting in an environment where ambiguity prevails.

Fear of Conflict

Lack of trust results in fear of conflict which in turn results in team members incapable of engaging in debates or openly voicing their opinions. 

The team completely avoids conflicts which results in inferior results.

Absence of Trust

It takes trust for team members to stand up for their weaknesses and to take responsibility for mistakes. 

How else would you ask for help if you pretend to be perfect?

If the trust is there, you win as a team!

As a Data Scientist or Machine Learning Engineer it's not easy to keep up with everything so good teamwork is crucial.

Why is MLOps important?

When the data changes, the machine learning models need to be readjusted and regularly deployed

- Continuous deployment (CD)

Why is MLOps important?

If your machine learning model is embedded in a complete project, it is probably not alone, we have an orchestra that plays and needs to be managed

- Continuous integration (CI)

Why is MLOps important?

Just because your model is hitting now doesn't mean it will be doing so 6 months from now

Model drift is real!

- Continuous training (CT)

The full MLOps life cycle

- Data Engineering: Get and clean the data recurring if necessary
- Model Engineering: Model training, evaluation, testing, and packaging
- Model Deployment: integrating the trained model. Model serving, performance monitoring

Did you think bringing your machine learning model to production was the hard part?

What about model drift?

Now MLOps comes into play but how does it work and what are good tools?

- Continuous deployment (CD)

Parrot

A practical and feature-rich paraphrasing framework to augment human intents in text form to build robust NLU models for conversational engines.

https://t.co/KqPka0od5F

But in general being a generative model paraphrasers doesn't guarantee to preserve slots/entities

So the ability to generate high quality paraphrases in a constrained fashion without trading off the intents and slots for lexical dissimilarity makes a paraphraser a good augmentor
The annotated data created out of the output paraphrases then makes the training dataset for your NLU model.
The output paraphrases are then converted into annotated data using the input annotations that we got in step 1.
Given an input utterance + input annotations a good augmentor spits out N output paraphrases while preserving the intent and slots.

What makes a paraphraser a good augmentor?

For training a NLU model we just don't need a lot of utterances but utterances with intents and slots/entities annotated. 

Typical flow would be:

1. Adequacy: Is the meaning preserved adequately?
2. Fluency: Is the paraphrase fluent English?
3. Diversity: Lexical / Phrasal / Syntactical ‚Üí how much has the paraphrase changed the original sentence?

But a good paraphrase should be adequate and fluent while being as different as possible on the surface lexical form. With respect to this definition, the 3 key metrics that measures the quality of paraphrases are:
For instance Neural Machine Translation outputs are tested for Adequacy and Fluency.

Almost all conditioned text generation models are validated on 2 factors:

1. If the generated text conveys the same meaning as the original context (Adequacy) 

2. If the text is fluent / grammatically correct english (Fluency)

FELIX uses three techniques to minimize the amount of required data: 

(1) fine-tuning pre-trained checkpoints, 
(2) a tagging model that learns a small number of edit operations, and 
(3) a text insertion task that is very similar to the pre-training task.

Compared to traditional seq2seq methods, FELIX has the following three key advantages:

Sample efficiency: Training a high precision text generation model typically requires large amounts of high-quality supervised data.
